post_text:
Aditya's NCShield.Org: Free Face Shields for Frontliners!

Triangle Senior Makes 3D-Printed Face Shields for Healthcare Workers

TMSA High School Student Aditya Shankar provides free face shields to as many healthcare and essential workers as he can in the RTP area.

He has already provided more than 150 face shields free of charge to those who risk their lives on the frontline to keep us safe against the pandemic.

When the lack of adequate PPE for frontline healthcare workers arose as a crisis, Aditya wanted to be a part of the solution and started to use his resources and skills for good.

Aditya has managed to produce face shields at a cost of $1.65. He needs your help to do more.

You can reach him at ncshield20@gmail.com or visit ncshield.org

#Healthcare #RTP #Faceshields #PPE #COVID19 #HelpHealthCareWorkers #TMSAPCS

post_text:
QCSS Secondary has some exciting updates!

1. The College and Career Website is now LIVE! This website will be the HUB for college and career resources and information for QCSS. The link will be available on the QCSS School Page soon, but for now, check it out here: http://bit.ly/qcsscollege

2. We will be having a Naviance Virtual Information Session for parents on September 10th from 5-6 PM. Naviance is the software that we will be using with students grades 6-10 (as well as 11th & 12th as we grow) to help them on their journey to post-secondary success! This event will be a chance to hear more about it and also learn more about College and Career at QCSS. We hope you can join us!

There's more to come, so stay tuned!

@NCPublicHealth: "Meningitis Vaccine Required All 12th Graders in NC Effective Aug. 1"

Effective Aug. 1, 2020, a booster dose of meningococcal conjugant vaccine (MenACWY) is required for students entering the 12th grade in public, private or religious schools in North Carolina. Students who do not meet this requirement may not be allowed to attend school until they receive the booster dose.

Teens and young adults are at increased risk for infection with meningococcal disease.

For more information on all vaccine requirements for 12th graders in North Carolina, go to www.immunize.nc.gov/schools.

post_text:
TMSA and QCSS Reopens with Plan C Online-Only For First Quarter

TMSA and QCSS Boards have decided in today's special meetings that our schools will reopen on August 11 with Plan C (full online) for the
first quarter. The Boards will re-evaluate the situation later in the quarter and will decide how to proceed for the next ones.

If the Boards decide to go with Plan B (hybrid) for the upcoming quarters in September, please note that a full online instruction will be an option for our students even under Plan B, so no need to worry
about the Virtual Academy registration.

post_text:
Dear TMSA and QCSS Communities,

Some parents have emailed us that they do not want to miss tomorrow’s deadline of Wake County Virtual Academy. As you know, our Boards will meet on Saturday to decide how to reopen our schools safely for our students and staff.

I would also remind you that Governor Cooper announced on July 14 that “[a]s a part of this plan [Plan B – Hybrid Learning], we want local school districts to provide remote learning options for any child who chooses it.”

﻿Even if our Boards decide to reopen with Plan B, we will continue to provide full remote learning for students who choose that option.

Please bear with us. Stay safe and strong!

Ben Karaduman
Superintendent

post_text:
Important Message:

TMSA Public Schools has made the decision to close for students due to the Covid-19 virus effective Monday, March 16, 2020.

This is an effort to protect our students, staff, and community, and to slow the spread of the virus.

The closure will take place over four weeks:

Week 1: (03/16/2020 - 03/20/2020).
“Asynchronous” distance learning – similar to the previous digital days format

Week 2: (03/23/2020 - 03/27/2020)
Includes an Early Spring Break for both TMSA and QCSS schools

Week 3&4: (03/30/2020 - 04/10/2020)
This will involve “Synchronous” or live video distance learning

All schools will resume their normal schedules on Monday April 13, 2020.

More details about options for distance learning and technological resources will be shared as soon as possible.

Week 2: (03/23/2020 - 03/27/2020)

This will involve “Synchronous” or live video distance learning

All schools will resume their normal schedules on Monday April 13, 2020.

More details about options for distance learning and technological resources will be shared as soon as possible.

post_text:
TMSA Public Charter Schools Community,

Effective immediately, all extracurricular activities, off-campus events, athletic programs (games, practices, etc...) field trips, and/or any employee-related travel is canceled until further notice. This does not include “in-house” field trips, which do not require students to leave school.

We are also cancelling Muffins for Moms and Thursday lunches with parents. Lunches for students can still be dropped off at the main office.

We are in communication with State and County health officials.

We will continue to monitor and make decisions as they are needed, and we will keep you advised. Please know that our number one priority is the safety and well-being of students and staff. Should you have any questions, please contact a member of the administrative team at Queen City STEM School.

post_text:
Bots on Wheels Team 4290 is currently recruiting for new students.

Bots on Wheels is a Charlotte based community robotics team available to any 9th through 12th graders in the greater Charlotte area. Students plan, design, program and build their competition robot with the help of their adult mentors.

Join us on September 10th at our meeting place at 900 Pressley Road in Charlotte from 6:00 PM – 8:00 PM to find out more about our team, meet our students, mentors and robot, Wheel Armstrong.

If you have questions about the team, feel free to contact via e-mail: svtriana0831@gmail.com or the team’s lead co-mentor, Cindy Carlson via phone: 704-649-2460 or via e-mail: BOWCommunityRobotics@gmail.com.

post_text:
We are Winners!

Our JV and Varsity Elementary Science Olympiad teams represented us so well in the District competition at UNC-Charlotte on May 18. We won a total of over 15 medals and our Queen City STEM Varsity TEAM came in 6th place overall out of 41 schools.

Our students won medals in events 3,2,1 Blast Off, Metric Mania, Ramp and Roll, Pasta Towers, Duct Tape Challenge, Body Builders, Work it Out, Science Sketchers, Ecology Experts, Super Sleuths, and Rock Star, as well as others.

We are so proud of our elementary Science Olympiad team.

post_text:
Recently, our young QCSS scientists on the Middle School Science Olympiad team competed at their regional competition here in Charlotte, NC. Science Olympiad is a fun, teamwork-based competition club, that requires students to showcase their science talents in different science events against other schools. They worked hard all year to learn more about science and prepare for their events!
Teams competing won 5th place in Circuit Lab and 5th place in the Fossils event and were very close to winning other awards as well! We are very proud of our Science Olympiad teams at QCSS and wanted to honor them and share their experience!

Congratulations!!!
Two of our students qualified for the MathCon final in Chicago, IL on Saturday, April 27th, 2019. Also, five of our students are on the waiting list and have a chance to qualify for the final. The final results will be announced on March 22nd. Proud of all our students who participated in the contest.

MathCon is an annual math contest for grade 5-12. There were 52000 participants from 550 schools across the nation last year. Every year, 100 students from each grade level are invited to the final round. For more information, please see the link: http://www.mathcon.org/

post_text:
AMC 8 (American Math Competitions) Results are Announced...

Congratulations to the winners and all participants.

The AMC 8 is a 25-question, 40-minute, multiple choice examination in middle school mathematics designed to promote the development of problem-solving skills. The AMC 8 provides an opportunity for middle school students to develop positive attitudes towards analytical thinking and mathematics that can assist in future careers. Students apply classroom skills to unique problem-solving challenges in a low-stress and friendly environment.

Enrollment for Math Kangaroo 2019 has started. You may register now. QCSS will be hosting the contest, and there are 200 spots. It is open to the public, get your spot before it gets full.

Math Kangaroo Competition is an international, once a year event. Every year on the third Thursday in March a huge number of students from all over the world take part in this important international mathematical competition.

If you have any questions, please email info@mathkangaroo.org or me (myigit@queencitystem.org).

For more info: https://mathkangaroo.oasis-lms.com/Public/Catalog/Home.aspx

Where: QCSS
When: @5 pm 3/21/2019

***Math Kangaroo invites STUDENTS and ADULTS to create a poster for the upcoming Math Kangaroo in USA competition. For more info: http://www.mathkangaroo.us/mk/pdf/2019PosterContestRules_2.pdf

QUEEN CITY STEM SCHOOL added 29 new photos — at Charlotte Convention Center.
June 28, 2018 at 6:39 PM · Charlotte, NC ·

Queen City STEM School students and principal, Mr. Ozer visited HydroVision Conference today. HydroVision International is the largest gathering of hydro professionals worldwide. The event highlights perspectives on the role of hydropower, explores issues affecting hydro resources, and helps participants develop a vision to meet challenges and ensure the future sustainability of hydro. At this event, the General Electric presented a $3,000 check to Queen City STEM School for its contribution to STEM education.

Finished up another humbling week by co-hosting the newly formed Charter School Business Network with NC Association Executive Director Rhonda Dillingham.

We aim to grow the opportunities for public charter schools and the business partnership that are so crucial to their fiscal and operational success.

Ultimately improving education opportunities across North Carolina.

A huge thank you to Principal Ali Ozer from Queen City Stem for hosting us.
